<font color="#FF0000">CHILDREN OF VETERANS</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jan 16 13:10:19 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
After three years of research on my own, I had the courage to ask my father directly about his experience in Vietnam.  It was obvious to me, even when I was very young, that VN severely hampered my father's feelings of self worth.  My father had three daughters and no sons, which certainly (to his mind anyway, I think) closed down any opportunities to tell war stories the way his father, a WWII vet, told him.  He is now classified as 80% service connected disabled, and has finally admitted that he needs counseling for PTSD, because I think, he gained back some of his self esteem by kicking his lifelong addiction to VA prescription drugs.  (Yeah, Dad!).  I am appalled to find out how many veterans are homeless, incarcerated or generally out of the loop of the &quot;happy&quot; civilian life the pre-VN '50s of their childhoods put them on the path toward.  Here's what I did:<br>
I knew that for my dad to get through this period in his life (closeted PTSD intensified by the feelings of a mid-life crisis, as well as drug addiction), I needed to come clean, and to tell him that I had been investigating VN on my own, and writing about my experiences as a child of a veteran (COV).  Now, believe it or not, even though I generally had an ok childhood, ie. Dad was there, didn't beat us, etc., VN had a huge impact on my outlook, values and morality.  For instance, VN taught my father not to be prejudiced, a lesson I learned from my father's experience, and so on.  The expereiences of COVs of surviving veterans is unique, and overlooked.  <br>
Together, my father and I are compiling an anthology by vets and COVs about their experiences (both good and bad) with the VN aftermath in their relationships.  The response has been surprising.  I would encourage you to add to the anthology, to begin (however much of a cliche it sounds like) the healing inside your own family.  It does seem strange for vet's children to take charge of this, but as I see it, in many ways, my father remains stuck in the jungle, a lost and upset 18 year-old.  This project has closed the chasm in my family, and has anwered many of my own personal anxieties and concerns.  I feel it is my duty to complete the project, and to promote this among so many other families who need an impetus for discussion.  We are still accepting submissions--you don't have to be a writer, just someone who wants to search for answers or become unburdened.  Please e-mail us for guidelines.<br>
All the best in your journeys.<br>

<p><code>-- jcolella@wam.umd.edu  (James and Jill Colella ) </code><p>


